CHAPTER SIXTEEN: Memory Crisis Peak
At 7:03 AM on Thursday, November 20, Miles woke without the usual negotiation.
The first fact was the time: 7:03, glowing on his phone where it lay face-up on the kitchen counter
—screen dim, battery at seventeen percent. He didn’t charge it overnight. He didn’t keep it in the 
bedroom. He left it out where he could see it and resent it: a small rule against waking into a digital 
trap and calling it reality. Wi-Fi off. Location off. A device reduced to clock and emergency line, 
nothing else. He kept it visible on purpose—so he couldn’t pretend it wasn’t there, and couldn’t let 
it become anything more.
The second fact was his body already upright, as if a silent instruction had executed before his mind
had the chance to object. Not sleepwalking. Not panic. Just a completed action with no conscious 
initiation, like his motor system had been granted a bypass.
Most mornings in the last five years began later—10:58, 12:14, 1:02—after hours in the thin halfsleep where the Windborn pressed its weight into his ribs and made waking feel like an unpaid debt.
He would lie still and build the day like a bridge with missing supports: how many steps to the 
kitchen, how much force required to stand, what failure would cost.
Today the calculation did not initiate.
He sat on the edge of the bed and waited for the familiar architecture to arrive.
It came, but altered.
The pressure was still in the room. It still sat behind his sternum—the old gravity that turned 
ordinary movement into an engineering problem. But it didn’t lock his joints. It didn’t pin him to 
the mattress.
It had shifted.
Load transferred to a beam he hadn’t approved, the kind of redistribution that looked like relief until
you found the crack later. He had learned to distrust improvements that arrived unearned. Systems 
didn’t donate capacity. They reallocated it.
In the corner by the window, the Windborn held its shape as a suggestion: a thin movement of 
